cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with covering problems in computational geometry, specifically the sensor cover problem and the restricted strip cover problem. These problems involve finding efficient ways to cover a given region using a set of geometric objects (sensors or intervals). Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also involves algorithmic techniques and analysis, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The use of approximation algorithms and constant factor approximations suggests that it could belong to cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) as well. Finally, the application of the results to sensor networks and wireless communication suggests that it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
